## Overview
Crowd-mapping is a tool used to aggregate people-generated inputs, such as geographic locations and descriptions of public drinking fountains.

## Purpose
The purpose of crowd-mapping in this context was to encourage the use of reusable water bottles by mapping public drinking fountains in Skopje, North Macedonia, and to stimulate conversation about their design and accessibility.

## How it works
Crowd-mapping involves using smartphones to geo-tag, photograph, and map locations, which are then aggregated on an interactive map. Participants can contribute to the map by following simple instructions and guidelines.

## Requirements
To effectively use crowd-mapping for R&D purposes, basic knowledge of creating a Google Map or other open map format is required, as well as access to smartphones for participants.

## Reflections
Considerations when using crowd-mapping include ensuring that participants have the necessary skills and resources to contribute to the map, and being mindful of the potential for biased or incomplete data.
